{
    "analysisCode": "from mpmath import mp, mpf\nimport json, math, statistics\n\nmp.dps = 50\n\n# Reconstruct the verification scenario\nN = 5\nstrict_majority = N // 2 + 1  # 3\n\n# Flexible quorum: R + W > N, minimize R with W = strict_majority for write safety\nflex_write = strict_majority  # 3 (preserve write safety)\nflex_read = N - flex_write + 1  # 3 (minimum for overlap)\n\n# But: can we go lower? R + W > N means R > N - W = 5 - 3 = 2, so R >= 3\n# For N=5, flex_read = strict_majority. No savings!\n# Try with W = 4: R > 5 - 4 = 1, so R >= 2. Now read saves 1 node.\n# But W=4 means HIGHER write latency — the claim omits this.\n\nresults_by_n = []\nfor n in range(3, 22, 2):\n    maj = n // 2 + 1\n    # Option 1: W = majority, minimize R\n    w1, r1 = maj, n - maj + 1\n    # Option 2: W = majority + 1, R can drop\n    w2, r2 = min(maj + 1, n), max(1, n - (min(maj + 1, n)) + 1)\n    results_by_n.append({\n        'N': n, 'majority': maj,\n        'equal_W': {'W': w1, 'R': r1, 'read_saving': maj - r1},\n        'higher_W': {'W': w2, 'R': r2, 'read_saving': maj - r2, 'write_cost': w2 - maj}\n    })\n\n# Key finding: when W = majority, R also = majority for odd N\n# Read savings ONLY come from increasing W above majority\nequal_w_savings = [r['equal_W']['read_saving'] for r in results_by_n]\nhigher_w_savings = [r['higher_W']['read_saving'] for r in results_by_n]\n\nresult = {\n    'actualValue': f'With W=majority: read savings = {equal_w_savings}. With W=majority+1: savings = {higher_w_savings}',\n    'expectedValue': 'Read latency reduction without write latency increase',\n    'deviation': f'For odd N with W=majority, R=majority — NO read savings. Savings require W>majority, increasing write latency.',\n    'alternativePattern': 'Flexible quorums trade write latency for read latency — not a free lunch. The claim omits that read savings require write quorum increases.',\n    'alternativeConfidence': 0.9,\n    'isInteresting': True,\n    'summary': f'The disproval reveals a fundamental trade-off the original claim missed: in flexible quorums with R+W>N, reducing R below majority requires increasing W above majority. For N=5 with W=3 (majority), R must also be 3 — identical to Raft. Read savings of 1 node only appear when W is raised to 4, which increases write latency. The claim that flexible quorums achieve lower read latency "without sacrificing write safety" is technically true but misleading — write LATENCY increases even though write SAFETY is preserved.'\n}",\n    "expectedFindings": "The analysis should reveal that for odd N, flexible quorums with W=majority yield R=majority — no read savings. Read latency reduction requires increasing W above majority, revealing a latency trade-off the original claim omitted."\n}",
    "expectedFindings": "The analysis should reveal that for odd N, flexible quorums with W=majority yield R=majority — no read savings. Read latency reduction requires increasing W above majority, revealing a latency trade-off the original claim omitted."
